{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622582"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:03:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:03:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16803"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16803"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9494"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76993"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9494"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16803"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62499"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5164"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23067"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76993"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPhenytoin is a commonly prescribed antiepileptic medication. Understanding its unique pharmacological properties is essential for safe prescribing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pharmacokinetic properties of phenytoin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Zero-order metabolism with no protein binding","First-order metabolism with linear elimination","Zero-order metabolism with 10% protein binding","First-order metabolism with 50% protein binding","Zero-order metabolism with 90% protein binding"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPhenytoin exhibits \u003Cstrong\u003Ezero-order metabolism with 90% protein binding\u003C/strong\u003E to albumin. This means that the rate of metabolism remains constant regardless of drug concentration, leading to potentially significant changes in serum levels with small dose adjustments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZero-order metabolism with no protein binding\u003C/strong\u003E - While the metabolism is correct, phenytoin is highly protein bound\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst-order metabolism with linear elimination\u003C/strong\u003E - Phenytoin notably exhibits zero-order (saturable) kinetics at therapeutic concentrations\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZero-order metabolism with 10% protein binding\u003C/strong\u003E - While the metabolism is correct, phenytoin is actually 90% protein bound\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst-order metabolism with 50% protein binding\u003C/strong\u003E - Both the metabolism type and protein binding percentage are incorrect\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese properties make phenytoin challenging to dose correctly. The high protein binding means changes in albumin levels can affect the free drug concentration. The zero-order kinetics mean that small dose increases can result in large and potentially toxic increases in drug levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Phenytoin is highly protein bound (90%) to albumin in the blood, which affects its free concentration and therapeutic effect.","Phenytoin exhibits zero-order (saturable) metabolism at therapeutic concentrations, meaning small dose increases can lead to large concentration changes.","The therapeutic range for phenytoin is narrow, requiring careful monitoring of drug levels."],"references":["Tanaka J, Kasai H, Shimizu K, Shimasaki S, Kumagai Y. Population pharmacokinetics of phenytoin after intravenous administration of fosphenytoin sodium in pediatric patients, adult patients, and healthy volunteers. Eur J Clin Pharmacol. 2013;69(3):489-497. doi:10.1007/s00228-012-1373-8","Rodriguez-Vera L, Yin X, Almoslem M, et al. Comprehensive Physiologically Based Pharmacokinetic Model to Assess Drug-Drug Interactions of Phenytoin. Pharmaceutics. 2023;15(10):2486. Published 2023 Oct 18. doi:10.3390/pharmaceutics15102486","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62499"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16803"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62499"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:04:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:06:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9494"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76993"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags